§2⁸. Mistake is of two kinds: it may exist either in forming an in· tention‚ or in expressing one¹ already genuinely formed. In this and the next section Justinian is speaking oi the latter. An error in a name, si de persona constat, does not affect the validity of a testamentary disposition, ‘rerum enim vocabula immutabilia sunt, hominum mutabilia’ Dig. 30 4 pr. Again, it a testator expressed a different quantity t'rom what be intended, the expression must yield to the intention, Dig. 28. 5. 9. 2-4; 3015: and is he inserted a condition which he never intended, it was taken pro non scripto, Dig. 28. 5. 5: but a disposition which in form is absolute, but which the testator intended to make conditional, is void, Dig. &595

A disposition made under a mistake, or in ignorance os certain facts (the first kind of mistake above mentioned) as a rule has all the effect which it would have had, had there been no mistake at all. In wills, however, this rute is reversed, and the disposition is void. Thus, iia testator institutes or gives a legacy to a person whom he erroneously believes to be his son or brother, the institution or legacy is invalid, Cod 6. 23. 5 ; 6. 244 7: so too if he institutes an extraneus supposing that he has no children of his own, Dig. 5. 2. 28, οι executes a second will under the impression that the person instituted in the first is dead, Dig. 28. 5. 92. According to this rule, the master of the instituted slave in Tit. 15. 4 supr. would be entitled to nothing, but the decision ot Tiberius, though quite opposed to principle, is to be excused as a rougb and ready attempt to adjust a condiet between equitable and strictly legal claims.
